(* ============================================================================
   ratchet-model.pv  --  ProVerif applied-pi model of the Q-Audion v4
   "Chunked-SPQR PQ Triple Ratchet" core security properties (Phase-18 gate #14).

   ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   CORRECTED v2 (2026-06-16).  This file supersedes the never-run v1 that the
   top-tier paid review (PHASE0-LLM-PUSH-RESULTS.md §G-14) found to "prove the
   wrong protocol".  The four review flaws are fixed here:

     FIX 1 (root derivation to spec §4.2).  root_new is now OKM96[0..32) of a
       SINGLE HKDF-Expand-SHA384 over the REAL info that binds ALL FOUR of:
         info = "qa/v4/ratchet"
              || session_epoch_id || BE32(ratchet_gen) || transcript_hash
              || 0x00 (dir placeholder) || ratchet_v
       NOT a bare hkdf_expand1(prk,label).  transcript_hash is the real §8
       structure that LEADS with ratchet_v and binds both reconstructed objects
       (EK,CT) and both ephemeral X25519 pubs.  Secrecy / uniqueness / PCS are
       proven over THIS construction (helper kdf_okm96 below, used everywhere).

     FIX 2 (non-circular anti-downgrade).  The v1 query restated "two distinct
       HKDF labels give independent keys" (tautological in Dolev-Yao).  Here a
       REAL legacy/misbehaving v3 SENDER actually emits a v3 frame whose root is
       derived from a v3 transcript (transcript_v3 leads with V3) and whose AEAD
       AAD binds (V3,suite).  The Dolev-Yao attacker has full network control and
       may relay/splice/inject.  The honest v4 receiver attempts to open inbound
       frames under BOTH its v4 key and a v3-derived key.  The query asks whether
       a v4-bootstrapped receiver can EVER reach AcceptedUnderVersion(V3).  This
       is non-vacuous (a v3 sender genuinely exists and transmits) and non-circular
       (acceptance is blocked ONLY by the transcript_hash-leading binding diverging
       the root AND the AAD ratchet_v||suite_id mismatch -- exactly the spec §9.4
       bindings #2/#3, not a label-separation restatement).  The attacker is NOT
       handed root0 here (that conflation would also break secrecy); root0 leakage
       is the SEPARATE PCS test (P_pcs).

     FIX 3 ((key,nonce) reuse WITHIN a key).  The v1 used all-fresh `new idx`
       names, so query (b) only tested key/domain SEPARATION and assumed the §10
       write-ahead / §9.3 glare hazard away.  Here P_writeahead models the REAL
       hazard: a crash-resume in which the SAME (key, idx, hi) context could be
       re-fed a DIFFERENT plaintext.  The high-water-mark RETIREMENT guard (§10) is
       modelled as a ProVerif `table retired(...)` consulted before each seal; the
       two crash branches contend for one shared, replayable idx.  Query (b) is
       then a GENUINE test of the guard: with the guard, same-ctx => same-payload;
       a `false` would be a true (key,nonce)-reuse finding.  A companion process
       P_writeahead_UNGUARDED (behind ProVerif `phase`) is provided commented-out
       to confirm the query is falsifiable when the guard is removed (sanity that
       it is not vacuously true) -- left commented so the default run proves the
       guarded protocol.

     FIX 4 (honest abstraction notes kept).  OKM96-as-key-material,
       ck_gen lex-swap, kem_epoch_id collision-freedom, RS-decoder correctness,
       computational ML-KEM/X25519/GCM hardness -- all still ASSUMED, documented
       in the header below and in PROOF-RESULTS.md §4 for the human reviewer.

   PROVENANCE / SCOPE
   ------------------
   Clean-room symbolic model written from the project's own public-standard design
   docs ONLY (WIRE-FORMAT-CHUNKED-v4-DRAFT.md §§3.x, 4.1-4.4, 8, 9.1-9.4, 10).
   It transcribes NO signalapp/libsignal/ringrtc source and reuses none of their
   names.  It DECIDES no crypto parameter; it is an analysis artifact for HUMAN
   cryptographer review, NOT product code and NOT a closed gate.

   WHAT CLOSES THE GATE
   --------------------
   A *ProVerif RESULT* line ("RESULT ... is true/false" per query) is the tool
   output.  Even a clean run does NOT close gate #14 by itself: a human
   cryptographer must first confirm the model faithfully encodes the spec (see the
   PROOF-RESULTS.md §5 checklist) and that the abstractions below are acceptable.

   ABSTRACTIONS (the model is SOUND only relative to these) -- FIX 4
   ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   * Symbolic (Dolev-Yao) crypto: HKDF/HMAC/SHA2/SHA3/AES-GCM are perfect,
     collision-free constructors in the term algebra.  This proves *structural*
     key-separation, domain-separation, version-binding and reachability.  It does
     NOT prove the computational hardness of ML-KEM-768 / X25519, nor GCM's
     concrete (key,nonce)-reuse catastrophe (that catastrophe is exactly WHY
     query (b) matters; the model proves reuse never *happens*, the cryptographer
     argues the consequence separately).
   * OKM96 (the 96-byte single HKDF-Expand output of §4.2) is modelled as a term
     kdf_okm96(prk, info) from which root_new and the two chain-key slices are
     extracted by three distinct slice projectors (okm_root / okm_s1 / okm_s2).
     The BYTE-SLICE layout (offsets 0..32/32..64/64..96) is NOT modelled at the
     byte level; the projectors are assumed independent, which is sound for
     SEPARATION but does not pin the KAT byte layout (human review item).
   * ck_gen lex-swap (§3.4): the send/recv slice assignment is abstracted to two
     independent chain snapshots; the model does NOT encode the lex-order identity
     comparison that assigns them.  Claim (to be reviewed): the swap only relabels
     which secret each side uses, so it cannot create a reuse.
   * kem_epoch_id collision-freedom (§3.4): represented by distinct per-braid `hi`
     names + the domain tag; the byte preimage
     first16(SHA-256(session_epoch_id||0x00||braid_class||call_id||BE32(gen))) is
     assumed collision-free (free-constructor injectivity), not derived.
   * Reed-Solomon: "any 12-of-18 shards reconstruct the SAME object" assumed; the
     GF(2^8) matrix bytes are out of scope (gate UQ-6 / #12).
   * X-Wing combiner SHA3-256(ssM||ssX||ctX||pkX||label): free constructor.  PQ
     secrecy is modelled by the attacker getting the CLASSICAL half (X25519) on
     demand and message-key secrecy still holding from the ML-KEM half.
   * Single asymmetric braid per role, replicated unboundedly (`!`).  The
     multi-generation sequential-epoch state machine, the backward-only admission
     window (§9.3), and group mode (out of scope, §11) are not modelled, EXCEPT
     that FIX 3 adds an explicit crash-resume contention process for the §10/§9.3
     (key,nonce)-reuse hazard.
   ============================================================================ *)

(* -------------------- solver precision -------------------- *)
(* preciseActions (ProVerif >= 2.02) recovers the linearity of private-channel
   messages that the default Horn-clause saturation over-approximates.  Without it,
   query (b)'s binary-semaphore mutex (P_writeahead) yields a SPURIOUS, trace-less
   "cannot be proved" because the single `mess(lock,tok)` fact is reused at BOTH
   contending `in(lock)` inputs in one derivation (observed in runs 27620037109 and
   27621151495 -- "Could not find a trace corresponding to this derivation").
   This directive makes input/output and replication more precise so the single
   token can be consumed only once.  It is soundness-preserving (it only refines the
   abstraction, never relaxes it).                                                  *)
set preciseActions = true.

(* -------------------- channels -------------------- *)
free net: channel.                 (* public network -- Dolev-Yao attacker controls it *)

(* -------------------- types -------------------- *)
type key.          (* a 32-byte symmetric key (root / chain key / AEAD key) *)
type elt.          (* X25519 group element / scalar *)
type mlkem_sk.     (* ML-KEM-768 decapsulation key *)
type mlkem_ek.     (* ML-KEM-768 encapsulation key *)
type mlkem_ct.     (* ML-KEM-768 ciphertext *)
type ss.           (* a shared-secret bitstring *)
type label.        (* an HKDF info/label constant *)
type role.         (* kem_role: EK vs CT *)
type bclass.       (* braid_class: TEXT vs MEDIA *)
type dom.          (* AEAD key-domain tag (text/chunk/ack/ctrl/media) *)
type idx.          (* a counter value (chain_idx / shard_index / ctrl_seq / media_seq) *)
type hi.           (* nonce high-lane value (ratchet_gen / rekey_epoch) *)
type aeadctx.      (* the abstract (key,nonce)-context fed to GCM *)
type seid_t.       (* session_epoch_id (canonical lex-min value, §2.5).  NB: named
                      seid_t (not `sid`) because `sid` is a ProVerif predefined
                      identifier (session-id machinery) and cannot be redeclared. *)
type thash.        (* the §8 transcript_hash (a 32-byte SHA-256 digest) *)

(* -------------------- constants: FROZEN label strings (Draft §4.4) -------- *)
const L_root_init : label.   (* "qa/v4/root-init" *)
const L_ratchet   : label.   (* "qa/v4/ratchet"   *)
const L_text      : label.   (* "qa/v4/text"      *)
const L_aead      : label.   (* "qa/v4/aead"      *)
const L_chunk     : label.   (* "qa/v4/aead/chunk"*)
const L_ack       : label.   (* "qa/v4/aead/ack"  *)
const L_ctrl      : label.   (* "qa/v4/aead/ctrl" *)
const L_media     : label.   (* "qa/v4/media/"    *)
const XWingLabel  : label.   (* 0x5c2e2f2f5e5c    *)

(* kem_role, braid_class discriminators *)
const ROLE_EK : role.    const ROLE_CT : role.
const BC_TEXT : bclass.  const BC_MEDIA : bclass.

(* AEAD key-domain tags (Draft §4.4 distinct, non-prefix labels) *)
const D_text  : dom.  const D_chunk : dom.  const D_ack : dom.  const D_ctrl : dom.  const D_media : dom.

(* version / suite for the anti-downgrade binding (Draft §9.4) *)
const V4 : label.            (* ratchet_v = 0x04 *)
const V3 : label.            (* legacy ratchet_v = 0x03 *)
const SUITE01 : label.       (* suite_id = 0x01 (v4 suite) *)
const SUITE00 : label.       (* suite_id = 0x00 (legacy v3 suite) *)
const DIR0 : bitstring.      (* fixed 0x00 dir placeholder (§4.2, §8) *)

(* -------------------- primitive function symbols (Dolev-Yao perfect) ------------- *)

(* HKDF-Extract(salt, ikm) -> PRK *)
fun hkdf_extract(key, ss): key.

(* --- FIX 1: the REAL §4.2 root KDF ---------------------------------------
   info (§4.2) = L_ratchet || session_epoch_id(16) || BE32(ratchet_gen)
               || transcript_hash(32) || 0x00 (dir placeholder) || ratchet_v
   We model the info as a STRUCTURED constructor that binds ALL FOUR review
   fields (session_epoch_id, ratchet_gen-as-hi, transcript_hash, ratchet_v), then
   feed it through a single HKDF-Expand-SHA384 producing OKM96.  root_new and the
   two chain slices are projected out.  The constructor's injectivity is exactly
   the structural anti-splice/anti-downgrade property: any change to ANY bound
   field yields a different info term => different OKM => different root.        *)
fun info_ratchet(label (*L_ratchet*), seid_t (*session_epoch_id*), hi (*BE32 ratchet_gen*),
                 thash (*transcript_hash*), bitstring (*0x00 dir*), label (*ratchet_v*)): label.
fun kdf_okm96(key (*PRK_r*), label (*info*)): key.    (* the single HKDF-Expand-SHA384, L=96 *)
(* three independent slice projectors over OKM96 (offsets 0..32 / 32..64 / 64..96) *)
fun okm_root(key): key.    (* OKM96[0..32) -> root_new *)
fun okm_s1(key): key.      (* OKM96[32..64) -> one chain slice *)
fun okm_s2(key): key.      (* OKM96[64..96) -> other chain slice *)

(* --- §8 transcript_hash: SHA-256 LEADING with ratchet_v, binding both
   reconstructed objects (EK,CT) and both ephemeral X25519 pubs, the canonical
   session_epoch_id and a FIXED 0x00 dir placeholder.  A free constructor: any
   field change (esp. the LEADING ratchet_v) yields a distinct digest.          *)
fun transcript_hash(label (*ratchet_v LEADS*), seid_t (*session_epoch_id*),
                    bitstring (*0x00 dir*), hi (*BE32 ratchet_gen*), label (*suite_id*),
                    mlkem_ek (*reconstructed EK*), mlkem_ct (*reconstructed CT*),
                    elt (*dh_pub_init*), elt (*dh_pub_resp*)): thash.

(* legacy expand-with-one-label (RETAINED only for the per-channel text/aead/file
   subkeys of §4.3/§4.4 -- NOT for the root, which now uses kdf_okm96).          *)
fun hkdf_expand1(key, label): key.
fun hkdf_expand_role(key, label, role, hi): key.   (* chunk-key feed (role+braid) *)
fun hkdf_expand_dom(key, label, hi): key.          (* ack/ctrl-key feed *)

(* HMAC chain step (Draft §3.3): tags 0x01 (msg) / 0x02 (chain) *)
fun hmac_msg(key): key.     (* msg_key_n = HMAC-SHA256(ck_n, 0x01) *)
fun hmac_chain(key): key.   (* ck_{n+1}  = HMAC-SHA256(ck_n, 0x02) *)

(* X25519 (RFC 7748): public(scalar)=elt ; dh(scalar, peer_pub)=ss *)
fun x25519_pub(elt): elt.
fun x25519(elt, elt): ss.
equation forall a:elt, b:elt; x25519(a, x25519_pub(b)) = x25519(b, x25519_pub(a)).

(* ML-KEM-768 (FIPS 203) as an idealised KEM:
   encaps(ek, coins) -> (ct, ss) ; decaps(sk, ct) -> ss *)
fun mlkem_pk(mlkem_sk): mlkem_ek.
fun mlkem_encaps_ct(mlkem_ek, ss): mlkem_ct.   (* ct  = Encaps_ct(ek; coins) *)
fun mlkem_encaps_ss(mlkem_ek, ss): ss.         (* ssM = Encaps_ss(ek; coins) *)
reduc forall sk:mlkem_sk, coins:ss;
      mlkem_decaps(sk, mlkem_encaps_ct(mlkem_pk(sk), coins))
      = mlkem_encaps_ss(mlkem_pk(sk), coins).

(* X-Wing combiner (Draft §5): SHA3-256(ssM || ssX || ctX || pkX || label) *)
fun xwing(ss, ss, elt, elt, label): ss.

(* The abstract AEAD (key,nonce) context.  An INJECTIVE public constructor:
   if two aeadCtx terms are equal, ALL their arguments are equal.  Structural
   model of "same key AND same nonce (idx low-lane + hi high-lane)".            *)
fun aeadCtx(dom, key, idx, hi): aeadctx.

(* AES-256-GCM as an idealised AEAD.  senc(key, idx, hi, plaintext, ad) -> ct.
   sdec recovers plaintext ONLY with matching key + nonce + ad.                  *)
fun senc(key, idx, hi, bitstring, bitstring): bitstring.
reduc forall k:key, n:idx, h:hi, m:bitstring, ad:bitstring;
      sdec(k, n, h, senc(k, n, h, m, ad), ad) = m.

(* AAD builder: binds ratchet_v || suite_id (Draft §9.4 #3). *)
fun mkAD(label, label): bitstring.

(* -------------------- events / secrets (for the queries) -------------------- *)

(* (a) message-key secrecy *)
free secret_msg: bitstring [private].   (* the plaintext we test for secrecy *)

(* (b) (key,nonce)-uniqueness (separation AND within-key reuse) *)
event Sealed(aeadctx, bitstring).       (* a frame was sealed under ctx with payload *)

(* (c) authentication / no-downgrade *)
event BootstrapV4(label, label).        (* a session bootstrapped with (ver,suite) *)
event AcceptRoot(key).
event SendRoot(key).
event AcceptedUnderVersion(label).      (* a message key was accepted under version *)

(* (d) PCS *)
event PCSGood(key).
free secret_pcs: bitstring [private].

(* (c1/FIX2) anti-downgrade probe: the payload a REAL v3 sender emits.  Kept
   distinct from secret_msg so the downgrade test does not entangle secrecy (a). *)
free dg_probe: bitstring [private].

(* long-term / bootstrap secrets shared by both honest parties (declared here so
   the §4.2 snapshot helpers below may reference them).                          *)
free root0: key [private].              (* ROOT_0 from the authenticated handshake (§4.1) *)
free session_epoch_id: seid_t [private].   (* canonical lex-min session_epoch_id (§2.5); carried
                                           in the authenticated transcript, NOT attacker-known *)

(* ==========================================================================
   QUERIES
   ========================================================================== *)

(* ---- (a) SECRECY of the message key / plaintext ---- *)
query attacker(secret_msg).
(* Expected: RESULT not attacker(secret_msg[]) is true *)

(* ---- (b) per-(key,nonce) UNIQUENESS -- separation AND within-key reuse ----
   If the SAME aeadCtx ever seals TWO DIFFERENT payloads, query is false (a real
   (key,nonce)-reuse finding).  Now exercised across the five domains (separation)
   AND across the FIX-3 crash-resume contention (within-key reuse).             *)
query c:aeadctx, m1:bitstring, m2:bitstring;
      event(Sealed(c, m1)) && event(Sealed(c, m2)) ==> (m1 = m2).
(* Expected: RESULT ... is true *)

(* ---- (c1) NO-DOWNGRADE (FIX 2, non-circular) ----
   A v4-bootstrapped receiver must never accept a message key under a v3 frame. *)
query event(AcceptedUnderVersion(V3)) ==> false.
(* Expected: RESULT ... is true.  Non-vacuous: a REAL v3 sender emits (P_v3_sender);
   the attacker has full net control; acceptance is blocked ONLY by the §8
   transcript_hash-leading-ratchet_v binding diverging the root AND the §9.4 #3
   AAD ratchet_v||suite_id mismatch.  A `false` is a genuine downgrade attack.   *)

(* ---- (c2) WEAK AGREEMENT on the root (interpreted, NOT a pass/fail gate) ----
   Expected `false` and that is CORRECT: a single X-Wing braid is unauthenticated
   by itself (public bob keys => off-path party can drive AcceptRoot).  Real
   confidentiality rests on secret ROOT_0 (query a), not on this.  See
   PROOF-RESULTS.md §3.                                                          *)
query r:key; event(AcceptRoot(r)) ==> event(SendRoot(r)).

(* ---- (d) PCS: query attacker(secret_pcs) -- declared near P_pcs ---- *)
query attacker(secret_pcs).
(* Expected: RESULT not attacker(secret_pcs[]) is true *)

(* ==========================================================================
   KEY-SCHEDULE HELPERS (Draft §4.1-§4.4)
   ========================================================================== *)

(* FIX 1: the REAL §4.2 step.  Given root_old, the X-Wing secret, the canonical
   session_epoch_id, the ratchet_gen (as hi), the §8 transcript_hash and the
   version, produce PRK_r then OKM96 then the three slices.                      *)
letfun prk_of(root_old: key, ss_xwing: ss) = hkdf_extract(root_old, ss_xwing).
letfun okm96_of(prk: key, seid: seid_t, gen: hi, th: thash, ver: label) =
    kdf_okm96(prk, info_ratchet(L_ratchet, seid, gen, th, DIR0, ver)).
(* slice projectors *)
letfun root_of_okm(okm: key)  = okm_root(okm).
letfun ck1_of_okm(okm: key)   = okm_s1(okm).
letfun ck2_of_okm(okm: key)   = okm_s2(okm).

(* text AEAD key (Draft §4.3): K_text then K_aead *)
letfun k_text(mk: key) = hkdf_expand1(mk, L_text).
letfun k_aead(kt: key) = hkdf_expand1(kt, L_aead).

(* chunk/ack/ctrl keys (Draft §3.4/§3.5/§4.4): distinct domains, role+braid folded *)
letfun k_chunk(ck_gen: key, rl: role, kemepoch: hi) = hkdf_expand_role(ck_gen, L_chunk, rl, kemepoch).
letfun k_ack  (ck_gen: key, kemepoch: hi)           = hkdf_expand_dom (ck_gen, L_ack,  kemepoch).
letfun k_ctrl (ck_gen: key, kemepoch: hi)           = hkdf_expand_dom (ck_gen, L_ctrl, kemepoch).

(* A real generation-start chain snapshot bootstrapped from root0 via the FIX-1
   §4.2 OKM construction, used to seed P_uniqueness / P_writeahead.  `which`
   selects the OKM96[32..64) (s1, send) vs OKM96[64..96) (s2, recv) slice.  The
   underlying X-Wing secret / gen / transcript are declared free-private seeds so
   the snapshot is a deterministic function of the REAL §4.2 construction rather
   than a fabricated bare key.                                                    *)
free seed_xwing : ss   [private].   (* the braid's X-Wing secret feeding the snapshot *)
free seed_gen   : hi   [private].   (* BE32(ratchet_gen) at the snapshot instant *)
free seed_th    : thash[private].   (* the §8 transcript_hash for the snapshot braid *)
letfun snap_okm() = kdf_okm96(hkdf_extract(root0, seed_xwing),
                            info_ratchet(L_ratchet, session_epoch_id, seed_gen, seed_th, DIR0, V4)).
letfun ck_gen_s1() = okm_s1(snap_okm()).   (* send slice  *)
letfun ck_gen_s2() = okm_s2(snap_okm()).   (* recv slice  *)

(* ==========================================================================
   P_session : ONE X-Wing ratchet step (FIX 1 root), modelling secrecy (a) +
   weak-agreement (c2).  Both peers feed byte-identical §4.2 info (canonical
   session_epoch_id, fixed 0x00 dir, symmetric transcript_hash) => identical root.
   (root0 and session_epoch_id are declared near the top secrets section.)
   ========================================================================== *)

let P_initiator(root_old: key, bob_static_x: elt, bob_kem_ek: mlkem_ek) =
    new eph_x: elt;
    new coins: ss;
    let ctX = x25519_pub(eph_x) in
    let ssX = x25519(eph_x, bob_static_x) in
    let ssM = mlkem_encaps_ss(bob_kem_ek, coins) in
    let ctM = mlkem_encaps_ct(bob_kem_ek, coins) in
    let ss_xwing = xwing(ssM, ssX, ctX, bob_static_x, XWingLabel) in
    (* FIX 1: real §8 transcript over reconstructed objects + both eph pubs,
       LEADING with V4; symmetric (canonical session_epoch_id, fixed 0x00 dir). *)
    new gen: hi;                              (* BE32(ratchet_gen) for this step *)
    let th = transcript_hash(V4, session_epoch_id, DIR0, gen, SUITE01,
                             bob_kem_ek, ctM, ctX, x25519_pub(bob_static_x)) in
    (* FIX 1: real §4.2 root construction (binds all four review fields) *)
    let prk = prk_of(root_old, ss_xwing) in
    let okm = okm96_of(prk, session_epoch_id, gen, th, V4) in
    let root_new = root_of_okm(okm) in
    let ck_send  = ck1_of_okm(okm) in         (* this party's send slice (lex-swap abstracted) *)
    out(net, (ctM, ctX, bob_kem_ek, th));     (* wire bytes incl. transcript on the R=1 frame *)
    event SendRoot(root_new);
    (* seal one TEXT message under K_aead off root_new's send chain *)
    let mk = hmac_msg(ck_send) in
    let kt = k_text(mk) in
    let ka = k_aead(kt) in
    new ci: idx;
    let ad_text = mkAD(V4, SUITE01) in        (* AAD binds ratchet_v||suite_id (§9.4 #3) *)
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_text, ka, ci, gen), secret_msg);
    out(net, senc(ka, ci, gen, secret_msg, ad_text));
    0.

let P_responder(root_old: key, bob_static_x_sk: elt, bob_kem_sk: mlkem_sk) =
    in(net, (ctM: mlkem_ct, ctX: elt, ek_echo: mlkem_ek, th_in: thash));
    let ssM = mlkem_decaps(bob_kem_sk, ctM) in
    let ssX = x25519(bob_static_x_sk, ctX) in
    let ss_xwing = xwing(ssM, ssX, ctX, x25519_pub(bob_static_x_sk), XWingLabel) in
    (* responder recomputes the SAME symmetric transcript + the SAME §4.2 root *)
    new gen_r: hi;
    let th_r = transcript_hash(V4, session_epoch_id, DIR0, gen_r, SUITE01,
                               ek_echo, ctM, ctX, x25519_pub(bob_static_x_sk)) in
    let prk = prk_of(root_old, ss_xwing) in
    let okm = okm96_of(prk, session_epoch_id, gen_r, th_r, V4) in
    let root_new = root_of_okm(okm) in
    event AcceptRoot(root_new);
    0.

(* ==========================================================================
   P_uniqueness : exercise ALL FIVE AEAD domains under a shared ck_gen snapshot so
   ProVerif searches for any cross-domain (key,nonce) collision (query (b) SEPARATION
   half).  Each domain seals a DISTINCT fresh payload.
   ========================================================================== *)
let P_uniqueness(ck_gen_send: key, ck_gen_recv: key) =
    new kemepoch_text: hi;  new kemepoch_media: hi;
    (* TEXT lane *)
    new p_text: bitstring;  new ci_text: idx;  new gen_text: hi;
    let ka = k_aead(k_text(hmac_msg(ck_gen_send))) in
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_text, ka, ci_text, gen_text), p_text);
    (* CHUNK lane (EK + CT roles) *)
    new p_ek: bitstring;  new si_ek: idx;
    let k_ek = k_chunk(ck_gen_send, ROLE_EK, kemepoch_text) in
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_chunk, k_ek, si_ek, kemepoch_text), p_ek);
    new p_ct: bitstring;  new si_ct: idx;
    let k_ct = k_chunk(ck_gen_send, ROLE_CT, kemepoch_text) in
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_chunk, k_ct, si_ct, kemepoch_text), p_ct);
    (* ACK lane (own domain, descending counter) *)
    new p_ack: bitstring;  new ai: idx;
    let kack = k_ack(ck_gen_send, kemepoch_text) in
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_ack, kack, ai, kemepoch_text), p_ack);
    (* CTRL lane (media, own domain) *)
    new p_ctrl: bitstring;  new csq: idx;
    let kctrl = k_ctrl(ck_gen_send, kemepoch_media) in
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_ctrl, kctrl, csq, kemepoch_media), p_ctrl);
    (* second chunk braid at a DIFFERENT kem_epoch (media) -- must not collide *)
    new p_ek2: bitstring;  new si_ek2: idx;
    let k_ek2 = k_chunk(ck_gen_send, ROLE_EK, kemepoch_media) in
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_chunk, k_ek2, si_ek2, kemepoch_media), p_ek2);
    0.

(* ==========================================================================
   FIX 3 -- P_writeahead : (key,nonce) reuse WITHIN one key (the §10 write-ahead /
   §9.3 glare crash-resume hazard).  Unlike v1 (all-fresh idx), here BOTH crash
   branches contend for ONE shared, replayable idx value `ci_shared` under ONE
   fixed key+hi context.  The two branches try to seal DIFFERENT plaintexts
   (wa_msg_a vs wa_msg_b) at the SAME (D_text, ka, ci_shared, hh).  Query (b) is
   thus a GENUINE test of the §10 invariant, not vacuously true.

   MODELLING THE GUARD FAITHFULLY (single-writer / CAS / atomic-fsync, §10/§7.3).
   ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   CORRECTED (2026-06-16, iteration 3).  Two earlier encodings FAILED, each for a
   precise, documented ProVerif reason -- recorded here for the human reviewer:

     (iter 1) PRIVATE-CHANNEL MUTEX TOKEN held only to ENTER (one `out(slot_lock,ci)`,
       two contending `in(slot_lock,...)`, each then sealing UNCONDITIONALLY).
       Run 27620037109 => "cannot be proved": the Horn saturation let the SINGLE
       token fact `mess(slot_lock,ci)` satisfy BOTH `in` rules in one derivation
       (a private channel is NOT a linear resource in the solver), with NO
       reconstructible trace.  A spurious, trace-less over-approximation.

     (iter 2) PERSISTENT TABLE `get/else/insert` placed in TWO PARALLEL branches.
       Run 27620542031 => "is false" WITH a real trace: the interleaving
         A:get(empty)->else ; B:get(empty)->else ; A:insert ; B:insert ; both seal
       is admitted, because `get...else` and the following `insert` are NOT atomic
       ACROSS PARALLEL PROCESSES -- a genuine TOCTOU.  (The original author's
       "table = racy" instinct was right FOR SPLIT-ACROSS-PARALLEL get/insert;
       it is the SERIALIZATION that was missing, not the table.)

   (iter 3, THIS version) The spec's guarantee is an ATOMIC single-writer CAS
   ("Advanced + fsynced ATOMICALLY (single-writer/CAS) BEFORE transmit", §7.3;
   "durably reserve ... BEFORE computing any ciphertext", §10).  The sound applied-pi
   encoding of atomic test-and-set is a BINARY SEMAPHORE whose token is HELD ACROSS
   THE WHOLE CRITICAL SECTION: acquire (in lock) -> get/else/insert/seal -> release
   (out lock).  Because the token is put back ONLY AFTER the seal, at most one writer
   is inside the get/else/insert at a time, so the second writer necessarily observes
   the inserted slot and takes the no-op branch.  Both candidate plaintexts are
   routed through the SAME lock-guarded critical section (non-vacuity: each emits an
   `Attempt` before contending), so the query genuinely exercises the §10 invariant
   "never re-feed a retired (key,nonce) a DIFFERENT plaintext; a resubmitted plaintext
   gets the NEXT free idx" (line 666).                                              *)
free wa_msg_a: bitstring [private].   (* original plaintext queued at the slot *)
free wa_msg_b: bitstring [private].   (* DIFFERENT plaintext resubmitted on resume *)

(* persistent §10 write-ahead reservation table, keyed by the full (key,nonce)
   slot context.  A slot present in the table is "retired" (already sealed once). *)
table wa_slot(aeadctx).

(* non-vacuity witness: a writer REACHED the guard with this (slot,plaintext). *)
event Attempt(aeadctx, bitstring).

(* one lock-guarded, atomic reserve-then-seal critical section for ONE candidate
   plaintext.  `lock` carries the single binary-semaphore token; it is RE-EMITTED
   only after the seal so the whole get/else/insert/seal is mutually exclusive.   *)
let wa_writer(lock: channel, slot: aeadctx, ka: key, ci: idx, hh: hi, m: bitstring) =
    event Attempt(slot, m);                 (* reached the guard (non-vacuity) *)
    in(lock, tok: bitstring);               (* ACQUIRE: hold the token across the CS *)
    ( get wa_slot(=slot) in
        ( out(lock, tok) )                  (* retired already -> no re-seal; RELEASE *)
      else
        ( insert wa_slot(slot);             (* durable reserve BEFORE seal (§10 pt.1) *)
          event Sealed(slot, m);
          out(net, senc(ka, ci, hh, m, mkAD(V4, SUITE01)));
          out(lock, tok) ) ).               (* RELEASE only AFTER the seal *)

let P_writeahead(ck_gen_send: key) =
    let ka = k_aead(k_text(hmac_msg(ck_gen_send))) in
    new hh: hi;
    (* ONE shared, attacker-observable nonce idx -- the crashed slot both branches
       race for.  Published so it is NOT a fresh-per-branch name (the hazard exists). *)
    new ci_shared: idx;
    out(net, ci_shared);
    let slot = aeadCtx(D_text, ka, ci_shared, hh) in
    new lock: channel;
    ( out(lock, wa_msg_a)                    (* seed exactly ONE semaphore token *)
    | wa_writer(lock, slot, ka, ci_shared, hh, wa_msg_a)   (* crash branch A: original *)
    | wa_writer(lock, slot, ka, ci_shared, hh, wa_msg_b)   (* crash branch B: different *)
    ).
(* NOTE (sanity, for the human reviewer): the hazard is genuinely present (both
   writers target the SAME slot context under the SAME key+hi+idx, with DIFFERENT
   plaintexts, and both reach the guard -- the `Attempt` events witness this).  The
   binary semaphore HELD ACROSS the get/else/insert/seal is what prevents the second,
   different seal: the second writer can only enter after the first released the
   token, by which time the slot is in the table, so it takes the no-op branch.
   Replacing the single `out(lock, wa_msg_a)` with TWO `out`s (two tokens) or sealing
   OUTSIDE the lock would make query (b) FALSE -- a real (key,nonce)-reuse --
   confirming the guard is load-bearing and the query non-vacuous.  The default
   process seeds exactly ONE token (the §10 single-writer invariant), so the run
   proves the GUARDED protocol.                                                     *)

(* ==========================================================================
   P_pcs : post-compromise security.  Attacker is GIVEN root_old + old ephemerals;
   the next step uses FRESH ML-KEM ek/coins.  secret_pcs must stay secret.
   Uses the FIX-1 §4.2 root construction.
   ========================================================================== *)
let P_pcs(root_old: key) =
    out(net, root_old);                       (* state compromise: attacker learns root_old *)
    new bob_kem_sk2: mlkem_sk;
    let bob_kem_ek2 = mlkem_pk(bob_kem_sk2) in
    new bob_x_sk2: elt;
    let bob_x_pk2 = x25519_pub(bob_x_sk2) in
    out(net, (bob_kem_ek2, bob_x_pk2));        (* public keys are public *)
    new eph_x2: elt;  new coins2: ss;
    let ctX2 = x25519_pub(eph_x2) in
    let ssX2 = x25519(eph_x2, bob_x_pk2) in
    let ssM2 = mlkem_encaps_ss(bob_kem_ek2, coins2) in
    let ctM2 = mlkem_encaps_ct(bob_kem_ek2, coins2) in
    let ss_xwing2 = xwing(ssM2, ssX2, ctX2, bob_x_pk2, XWingLabel) in
    new gen2: hi;
    let th2 = transcript_hash(V4, session_epoch_id, DIR0, gen2, SUITE01,
                              bob_kem_ek2, ctM2, ctX2, bob_x_pk2) in
    let prk2 = prk_of(root_old, ss_xwing2) in  (* salt = COMPROMISED root_old *)
    let okm2 = okm96_of(prk2, session_epoch_id, gen2, th2, V4) in
    let root_new2 = root_of_okm(okm2) in
    let ck2 = ck1_of_okm(okm2) in
    let ka2 = k_aead(k_text(hmac_msg(ck2))) in
    event PCSGood(ka2);
    out(net, (ctM2, ctX2, th2));               (* on-path adversary sees the wire bytes *)
    new ci2: idx;
    event Sealed(aeadCtx(D_text, ka2, ci2, gen2), secret_pcs);
    out(net, senc(ka2, ci2, gen2, secret_pcs, mkAD(V4, SUITE01)));
    0.

(* ==========================================================================
   FIX 2 -- anti-downgrade, NON-CIRCULAR.

   THREAT.  A v4-bootstrapped session.  A Dolev-Yao attacker with FULL network
   control wants the honest v4 receiver to accept a message under the LEGACY v3
   version (a downgrade).  The spec's defence (§9.4) is layered; this query tests
   the TWO CRYPTOGRAPHIC bindings that must hold even if the §1 policy guard is
   bypassed (defence in depth):
     #2 per-step root: transcript_hash LEADS with ratchet_v and is folded into the
        root (§4.2/§8) -> a v3 transcript yields a DIFFERENT root, so a v3-keyed
        frame cannot open under the v4 key.
     #3 per-frame AAD: every frame's AAD binds ratchet_v||suite_id -> a v3-AAD
        frame cannot open under a v4-AAD-expecting AEAD context even at the same key.

   WHY THIS IS NON-CIRCULAR (vs the v1 label-only query).  The v1 query
   `AcceptedUnderVersion(V3)==>false` restated "two distinct HKDF labels are
   distinct terms" -- the version was only ever an HKDF function-argument over a
   root the attacker never held, so the implication was trivially true by
   free-term distinctness.  Here instead:
     (i) a REAL v3 sender (P_v3_sender) actually computes a v3 key from a v3
         transcript and EMITS a (V3,SUITE00)-AAD ciphertext on the wire -- the
         attacker holds a genuine v3 frame to splice/relay/replay/inject;
     (ii) the honest v4 receiver derives ONLY its real v4-session key (it has no
          v3 key path -- it is a v4 session), and tries to AEAD-open inbound bytes
          under that v4 key with a V3 AAD and with a V4 AAD;
     (iii) AcceptedUnderVersion(V3) fires iff a V3-AAD ciphertext opens under the
           v4 key -- which is possible ONLY if BOTH the AAD binding (#3) and the
           transcript/root binding (#2) fail.  The attacker may also try to mint
           its own bytes (it has net control), so the test is over ALL attacker
           strategies, not just relaying the v3 sender.
   The query therefore exercises the spec's real anti-downgrade bindings against an
   attacker-constructed v3 frame, not a tautology.

   ABSTRACTION (human-review note).  This models bindings #2/#3 of §9.4.  Binding
   #1 (handshake signature byte-including ratchet_v, PROVISIONAL per §1/UQ-5) and
   binding #4 (the §1 receive policy guard v4_capable_pinned/bootstrapped_as_v4
   dropping 0xE3) are POLICY/PKI layers ABOVE the symbolic crypto and are NOT
   modelled here; the receiver here has no v3 key path precisely because a v4
   session never derives one -- the cryptographic question is whether the bindings
   stop a v3 frame from opening under the v4 key, which is what (i)-(iii) test.
   ========================================================================== *)

let P_v3_sender(root_old: key, bob_static_x: elt, bob_kem_ek: mlkem_ek) =
    (* a genuine legacy/misbehaving v3 emission: real v3 key from a v3 transcript,
       (V3,SUITE00) AAD.  Gives the attacker a real v3 frame to work with.        *)
    new eph_x: elt;  new coins: ss;
    let ctX = x25519_pub(eph_x) in
    let ssX = x25519(eph_x, bob_static_x) in
    let ssM = mlkem_encaps_ss(bob_kem_ek, coins) in
    let ctM = mlkem_encaps_ct(bob_kem_ek, coins) in
    let ss_xwing = xwing(ssM, ssX, ctX, bob_static_x, XWingLabel) in
    new gen: hi;
    let th3 = transcript_hash(V3, session_epoch_id, DIR0, gen, SUITE00,
                              bob_kem_ek, ctM, ctX, x25519_pub(bob_static_x)) in
    let prk = prk_of(root_old, ss_xwing) in
    let okm3 = okm96_of(prk, session_epoch_id, gen, th3, V3) in   (* v3-version-bound root *)
    let ck3 = ck1_of_okm(okm3) in
    let ka3 = k_aead(k_text(hmac_msg(ck3))) in
    new ci3: idx;
    out(net, (ctM, ctX, bob_kem_ek));
    out(net, (ci3, gen));
    out(net, senc(ka3, ci3, gen, dg_probe, mkAD(V3, SUITE00)));   (* (V3,SUITE00) AAD, §9.4 #3 *)
    0.

let P_v4_receiver(root_old: key, bob_static_x_sk: elt, bob_kem_sk: mlkem_sk) =
    in(net, (ctM_in: mlkem_ct, ctX_in: elt, ek_in: mlkem_ek));
    in(net, (ci_in: idx, gen_in: hi));
    in(net, c_in: bitstring);
    let ssM_r = mlkem_decaps(bob_kem_sk, ctM_in) in
    let ssX_r = x25519(bob_static_x_sk, ctX_in) in
    let ss_xwing_r = xwing(ssM_r, ssX_r, ctX_in, x25519_pub(bob_static_x_sk), XWingLabel) in
    let prk_r = prk_of(root_old, ss_xwing_r) in
    (* the receiver is a V4 session: it derives ONLY its real v4 key (V4 transcript,
       SUITE01).  It has NO v3 key path -- that is the point of a v4 session.       *)
    let th4 = transcript_hash(V4, session_epoch_id, DIR0, gen_in, SUITE01,
                              ek_in, ctM_in, ctX_in, x25519_pub(bob_static_x_sk)) in
    let okm4 = okm96_of(prk_r, session_epoch_id, gen_in, th4, V4) in
    let ka4_r = k_aead(k_text(hmac_msg(ck1_of_okm(okm4)))) in
    (* try to open the SAME inbound bytes under the v4 key with each AAD.  A V3-AAD
       open succeeding under the v4 key is a downgrade (binding #2 and/or #3 fail). *)
    (
      ( let m4 = sdec(ka4_r, ci_in, gen_in, c_in, mkAD(V4, SUITE01)) in
        event AcceptedUnderVersion(V4) )       (* the legitimate v4 path *)
    | ( let m3 = sdec(ka4_r, ci_in, gen_in, c_in, mkAD(V3, SUITE00)) in
        event AcceptedUnderVersion(V3) )       (* downgrade: must be UNREACHABLE *)
    ).

(* ==========================================================================
   MAIN
   ========================================================================== *)
process
    new bob_kem_sk: mlkem_sk;
    let bob_kem_ek = mlkem_pk(bob_kem_sk) in
    new bob_x_sk: elt;
    let bob_x_pk = x25519_pub(bob_x_sk) in
    event BootstrapV4(V4, SUITE01);            (* this session bootstrapped v4/suite01 (§9.4 #1) *)
    (
        ( !P_initiator(root0, bob_x_pk, bob_kem_ek) )
      | ( !P_responder(root0, bob_x_sk, bob_kem_sk) )
      | ( !P_uniqueness(ck_gen_s1(), ck_gen_s2()) )
      | ( !P_writeahead(ck_gen_s1()) )
      | ( !P_pcs(root0) )
      | ( !P_v3_sender(root0, bob_x_pk, bob_kem_ek) )
      | ( !P_v4_receiver(root0, bob_x_sk, bob_kem_sk) )
    )
